definition.value: The S-oxide derivative of methionine. It is a biomarker of oxidative stress.
A ketoaldonic acid derivative that is the 6-(dihydrogen phosphate) derivative of 3-dehydro-L-gulonic acid.

An amino acid amide in which 2-[ethyl(propyl)amino]butanoic acid  and 2,6-dimethylaniline have combined to form the amide bond. Used as a local anaesthetic (amide caine), it has rapid onset and long action properties, similar to bupivacaine, and is given by injection during surgical procedures and during labour and delivery.
A beta-lactam that is azetidin-2-one which is substituted at 1, 3, and 4 by p-fluorophenyl, 3-(p-fluorophenyl)-3-hydroxypropyl, and  4-hydroxyphenyl groups, respectively (the 3R,3'S,4S enantiomer).
The nitro compound formed from propan-1-ol by nitration at C-3.
The ureido derivative of malonic acid.
Any  carboxylic acid carrying a carbamoylamino group.
An organic sodium salt resulting from the replacement of two protons from etidronic acid (one from from each of the phosphonic acid groups) by sodium ions.
Groups formed by removing one or more hydroxy groups from thioxoacids that have the general structure RkE(=S)l(OH)m (l =/= 0), and replacement analogues of such thioacyl groups.
A univalent carbothioacyl group is a group formed by loss of OH from the thiocarboxy group of a thiocarboxylic acid.
A divalent carbothioacyl group is a group formed by loss of OH from two thiocarboxy groups of a polythiocarboxylic acid.
A 4-phosphothreonic acid derived from D-threonic acid.

A  1,1-bis(phosphonic acid) that is (ethane-1,1-diyl)bis(phosphonic acid) having a hydroxy substituent at the 1-position. It inhibits the formation, growth, and dissolution of hydroxyapatite crystals by chemisorption to calcium phosphate surfaces.
